{{Notelist}}
*

Illish pronouns use many English neopronouns
Over time the pronoun system became more regularized due to the presence of neopronouns
This includes
* the eventual development of an -m suffix on all object forms ** Started with the neopronouns ** Moved to Me becoming Meme since it is reduplication ** Then Youm ** Then finally Us became Um after pronounciation became too similar to Ours * all dependent possessives end with -ra (a stronger enunciation of the -r after it started to get challenged by tonogenesis, similar things happened on rising tone final syllable words and on the various grammatical suffixes that later became the tone Suprafixes.) *
{| class="wikitable" ! ! colspan="2" |Subject ! colspan="2" |Object ! colspan="2" |Dependent pos ! colspan="2" |Independent pos ! colspan="2" |Reflexive |- ! ! English ! Illish !English!! Illish !English!! Illish !English!! Illish !English!! Illish |- | Informal 1st person | I | Aī |Me|| Mīm |My|| Maīra |Mine|| Mãīs |Myself|| Maīseēf |- | Formal 1st person | We | Wī |Us|| Ām |Our|| Arā |Ours|| Aās |Ourself|| Aāseēf |- | 2nd person | You | Yū |You|| Yūm |Your|| Yoōrā |Yours|| Yoōs |Yourself|| Yoōseēf |- | 3rd person (animate) | They | Deī |Them|| Dēm |Their|| Deērā |Theirs|| Deēs |Theirself|| Deēseēf |- | Inanimate | It | I |It|| I |Its|| I |Its|| I |Itself|| Iseēf |- | 4th person | Fae | Feī |Faem|| Fēm |Faer|| Feērā |Faers|| Feēs |Faerself|| Feēseēf |- |5th person |Xe |Zeī |Xem |Zēm |Xeir |Zeērā |Xeirs |Zeēs |Xeirself |Zeēseēf |- | 6th person | She | Sheī |Her|| Shem |Her|| Sheērā |Hers|| Sheēs |Herself|| Sheēseēf |- | 7th person | He | Heī |Him|| Hem |His|| Heērā |His|| Heēs |Himself|| Heēseēf |- | 8th person | Vi | Veī |Vim|| Vēm |Vir|| Veērā |Virs|| Veēs |Virself|| Veēseēf |- | 9th person | Ne | Neī |Nem|| Nēm |Neir|| Neērā |Neirs|| Neēs |Neirself|| Neēseēf |- | 10th person | Per | Peī |Per|| Pēm |Per|| Peērā |Pers|| Peēs |Perself|| Peēseēf |}
== Change timeline == We are only including the singular tone for this purpose
=== I === {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom (Subject) ! Acc (Object) ! Dat (Indirect Obj) ! Dependent pos ! Independent pos ! Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | *éǵh₂ | *mé | *moi | (genitive forms only)<ref>PIE did not have dependent possessives; possession was expressed by genitive case.</ref> | (n/a) | (n/a) | All cases distinct |- | Proto-Germanic | *ik | *mik | *miz | (from *meina) | (n/a) | (n/a) | 4-case system; all distinct |- | Old English (450–1100) | '''ic''' | '''me''' | '''me''' | '''mīn''' | '''mīn''' | ''ic self''<ref>“self” was still a fully inflected noun in OE and not yet part of a reflexive pronoun.</ref> | First major merger: acc/dat → "me" |- | Middle English (1100–1500) | '''I''' | colspan="2" | '''me''' | '''my''' | '''mine'''<ref>Independent possessive ("mine") arises from phonological full-vs-reduced alternation.</ref> | '''myself'''<ref>Reflexives originate from pronoun + “self,” which was reanalyzed as a bound morpheme.</ref> | Possessive splits by analogy → my/mine |- | Modern English | '''I''' | colspan="2" | '''me''' | '''my''' | '''mine''' | '''myself''' | Reflexive created analogically |- |Illish |Aī | colspan="2" |Mīm<ref>-m object form came back in analogy with neopronouns and reduplication</ref> |Maī |Maīn |Maīseēf |Became informal 1st person after tones started to mark number |}
=== We === {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom (Subject) ! Acc (Object) ! Dat ! Dependent pos ! Independent pos ! Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | *wéy | *ns-me | *ns-moi | *ns-osyo (genitive) | (n/a) | (n/a) | PIE used case endings, not separate possessives |- | Proto-Germanic | *wīz | *uns | *uns | *unsara | (same) | Reflexive only for 3rd person (*sik*) | 4-case system; acc/dat already converging |- | Old English (450–1100) | '''wē''' | '''ūs''' | '''ūs''' | '''ūre''' | '''ūre''' | ''wē selfe''<ref>OE “self” was still an independent noun, not a bound reflexive suffix.</ref> | Acc/dat fully merged into “ūs” |- | Middle English (1100–1500) | '''we''' | '''us''' | '''us''' | '''our''' | '''ours'''<ref>Independent possessive arises by same analogy as my/mine, thy/thine, their/theirs.</ref> | '''ourselves'''<ref>Reflexive created from pronoun + “selves” by Middle English analogy.</ref> | Possessive splits by analogy → our / ours |- | Modern English | '''we''' | colspan="2" | '''us''' | '''our''' | '''ours''' | ourselves | Stable plural paradigm; reflexive fully grammaticalized |- |Illish |Wī | colspan="2" |Ām<ref>Because Aās and As were too close ended up taking -m by analogy. Last of the pronouns to do that</ref> |Aā |Aās |Aāseēf |Became formal 1st person after tones started to mark number |}
=== You === {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom (Subject) ! Acc (Object) ! Dat ! Dependent pos ! Independent pos ! Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | *túh₂ | *té | *toi | (genitive forms only) | (n/a) | (n/a) | All distinct |- | Proto-Germanic | *þū | *þek | *þiz | *þeina | (n/a) | (n/a) | Distinct forms |- | Old English (singular) | '''þū''' | '''þē''' | '''þē''' | '''þīn''' | '''þīn''' | ''þū self'' | Singular kept distinctions |- | Old English (plural) | '''gē''' | '''ēow''' | '''ēow''' | '''ēower''' | '''ēower''' | ''gē selfe'' | Plural also distinct |- | Middle English | thou / ye | thee / you | thee / you | thy / your | thine / yours | thyself / yourself | Start of mergers; "you" rises as polite singular |- | Early Modern | '''you''' | colspan="2" | '''you''' | '''your''' | '''yours''' | yourself / yourselves | SUBJECT/OBJECT merge fully |- | Modern English | '''you''' | colspan="2" | '''you''' | '''your''' | '''yours''' | yourself / yourselves | Most collapsed pronoun paradigm |- | |Yū | colspan="2" |Yūm |Yoō |Yoōs |Yoōseēf | |- |Illish |ju | colspan="2" |jɛm<ref>Object came back in analogy with neopronouns and Me/Meme</ref> |jo'''ː''' |jo'''ːs''' |jo'''ː'''sɛ˥f | |} === He === {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom ! Acc ! Dat ! Dependent pos ! Independent pos ! Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | *h₁éy / *so | *(h₁)eṃ | *éyemi | *ésyo | (n/a) | (n/a) | No true 3rd-person; demonstratives used |- | Proto-Germanic | *iz | *iną | *im | *is | (same) | Reflexive *sik* | Full case system; acc/dat distinct |- | Old English | '''hē''' | '''hine''' | '''him''' | '''his''' | '''his''' | ''hē self'' | Acc & dat distinct |- | Late Old English | '''hē''' | ('''him''' replaces hine) | '''him''' | '''his''' | '''his''' | ''him self'' | Acc → dat merger begins |- | Middle English | '''he''' | '''him''' | '''him''' | '''his''' | '''his''' | '''himself''' | Merger complete; no new analogies |- | Modern English | '''he''' | colspan="2" | '''him''' | '''his''' | '''his''' | himself | Stable paradigm |- | |He | colspan="2" |Him |Hir |Hir |Hirself | |- |Illish |Heī | colspan="2" |Hēm |Heē |Heēs |Heēseēf |Reduced to marginal usage and pronounciation taken from they |} === Her === {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom ! Acc ! Dat ! Dependent pos ! Independent pos ! Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | (demonstratives) | (demonstratives) | (demonstratives) | (demonstratives) | (n/a) | (n/a) | PIE had no 3rd-person personal pronoun |- | Proto-Germanic | (demonstrative forms) | (demonstrative forms) | (demonstrative forms) | (demonstrative genitives) | (n/a) | (n/a) | Feminine derived from demonstratives |- | Old English | '''heo''' | '''hīe''' | '''hire''' | '''hire''' | '''hire''' | ''hēo self'' | Acc = hīe; dat/gen = hire |- | Middle English | '''she'''<ref>Origin likely from Anglian "scho" or reanalysis of OE "seo".</ref> | '''her''' | '''her''' | '''her''' | '''hers'''<ref>Independent possessive created by analogy with mine/thine.</ref> | '''herself''' | Massive mergers: acc/dat/gen → "her" |- | Modern English | '''she''' | colspan="2" | '''her''' | '''her''' | '''hers''' | herself | Most collapsed 3rd-person system |- |She line |She | colspan="2" |Shem |Sher |Shers |Shemself/Herself | |- |Her line |Her | colspan="2" |Herm |Her |Hers |Herself | |- |Illish |Sheī | colspan="2" |Shēm<ref name=":0">Pronounciation taken from they/them with just the sh- initial kept
However many consider this the successor pronoun. The same [[kanji]] is used across both.</ref> |Sheē<ref name=":0" /> |Sheēs<ref name=":0" /> |Sheēseēf<ref name=":0" /> |Reduced to marginal usage and pronounciation taken from they |} ===They=== {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom (Subject) ! Acc (Object) ! Dat ! Dependent pos ! Independent pos ! Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | (demonstratives) | (demonstratives) | (demonstratives) | (demonstratives) | (n/a) | (n/a) | PIE had no personal pronoun for 3rd-plural |- | Proto-Germanic | *þai | *þanz | *þaim | *þaizō | (same) | Reflexive *sik* | Distinct paradigms |- | Old English (native) | '''hīe''' | '''hīe''' | '''him''' | '''heora''' | '''heora''' | ''hīe selfe'' | Native forms (not ancestors of modern “they”) |- | Old Norse (borrowed set) | '''þeir''' | '''þá''' | '''þeim''' | '''þeira''' | '''þeira''' | ''þeir sjálfr'' | Distinct 4-case paradigm; borrowed in Danelaw |- | Middle English (early) | they | them | them (dat merged) | their | theirs | themselves<ref>“selves” ending created by analogy with our/your + selves.</ref> | Norse forms replace English ones |- | Middle English (late) | '''they''' | colspan="2" | '''them''' | '''their''' | '''theirs''' | themselves | Possessive splits by analogy |- | Modern English | '''they''' | colspan="2" | '''them''' | '''their''' | '''theirs''' | themselves / themself<ref>“Themself” appears in the 1300s; revived for singular they.</ref> | Stable paradigm; also used as singular |- |Illish romanization |Deī | colspan="2" |Dēm |Deē |Deēs |Deēseēf | |- |Illish |ðeɪ | colspan="2" |dɛm |ðɛɚ |ðɛɚz |ðɛɚsɛ˥f | |} === It === {| class="wikitable" ! Stage ! Nom ! Acc ! Dat ! Dependent pos !Independent pos !Reflexive ! Notes |- | Proto-Indo-European | (inanimate demonstratives) | (inanimate demonstratives) | (inanimate datives) | (genitive demonstratives) | (n/a) | (n/a) | Inanimates did not use reflexives |- | Proto-Germanic | *þat | *þat | *þata | *þas | (same) | (n/a) | All demonstrative-based |- | Old English | '''hit''' | '''hit''' | '''him''' | '''his''' | '''his''' | ''hit self'' | Nominative = accusative |- | Middle English | '''it''' | '''it''' | '''it''' | '''its'''<ref>“its” emerges in 17th century; before that, “his” used for neuter possessive.</ref> | '''its''' | itself | Dat merges; "its" appears in 1600s |- | Modern English | '''it''' | '''it''' | (merged) | '''its''' | '''its''' | itself | Total collapse except possessive |- |Illish |ɪ˩ |ɪ˩ |ɪ˩ |ɪ˩ |ɪ˩ |ɪ˩sɛ˥f |Tone removed coda and genitives lost |}
== References ==

Non concatenative morphology occurs across all roots in roughly this form {| class="wikitable" | |'''Operation''' |'''Mnemonic name (Aelaki)''' |'''Form''' |'''Core meaning''' |- |Base |'''Base''' |''bhinki‑'' “root” |C₁V₁C₂V₂C₃ |singular / perfective‑incomplete / positive degree |- |Plural |'''Reduplication''' |''bhinkibhin'' “two roots” |C₁V₁'''C₂'''C₂V₂C₃ |partitive plural / imperfective / comparative |- |Complete |'''Umlaut''' |''bhinkiæ'' “final root” |C₁'''front‑V₁'''C₂'''front‑V₂'''C₃ |collective / perfective‑completed / superlative |- |Negation |'''Zero‑infix''' /ɸ/ |''bhinki‑f'' “absent root” |C₁V₁'''f'''C₂V₂C₃ |negation / zero quantity |}
== Notes == Negation form is not present in particles, because particles tend to be 1 syllable long, and as a result too short for the infix to be properly added
